Text.Value: You can't leave us like this. You're the first person who's heard the real me in months.
Why would I help you after what you did to your own son?
I know what you did. I know that you sold your son into slavery.
We had debts. World-ending debts, trying to keep this cursed shop afloat. Dangerous lenders who said they'd bury us all if we didn't pay.
Put her out of her misery - violently.
Help me. Dear gods, help me!
I hope he rots in the Hells, where he belongs. He always was a nasty little monster.
Maybe. Maybe not. It's for the gods to judge me - not my wicked son. And not you.
He was always a little monster. Nasty to the core. He would've torn me and Dravo apart with his whining, his demands, the never-ending racket of him!
*You search her mind, but the psionic forces that control her are different - split, somehow. Your own consciousness slips into the gap.*
We got good coin for him. Closed our debts, and all of us kept our lives - Enver included.

EditorData.NodeContext: 'tiefling' spat out with hatred. She's a racist nasty.

Text.Value: *Your tadpole squirms. These people are infected with the parasite - but something is... off.*
Gortash's mum, huh?
A pleasure to meet the mother of the Archduke.
We're celebrating our dear son's magnificent achievement with a special run of leather-soled shoes.
Do I take it you're Lord Gortash's mother?
Connect your tadpole to hers - delve into her mind.
Probe her mind.
May he rest in peace, our sweet boy. This world will never see his like again.
We hadn't seen him in so long. I knew he was an animal, but I underestimated him.
A very fair trade, if you ask me.
End her suffering - attack.
Leave.
You deserve what you got - and more.
You can't leave me like this. You can't leave me in this hell!
Oh. Oh no. You have things very, very wrong. A dutiful mother would never do something so heinous. A good mother couldn't have fathomed such a horror.

EditorData.NodeContext: A little uncanny, since the paradox of her brain is being called into question.

Text.Value: You've chosen the wrong household to argue politics, my friend. Shop, if you like, but let's talk no more of my son.
Do I take it you're Lord Gortash's mother?
Our son, the city's saviour Enver Gortash, was slain by Absolutist conspirators.
You may not have intended to, but you created a monster.
I can put you out of your misery, if you like.
So you're to blame for the rise of that charlatan.
I'm here. But I can't speak. I can't act. I'm trapped.
Leave.
Wait! WAIT!
Then, a warlock offered us a pretty penny for Enver's service. He was a smart boy - too smart. It was give him up - and all of us live - or refuse, and die.
Don't you judge me, tiefling. We got good coin for him. Closed our debts, and all of us kept our lives - Enver included.
His one and only. My, but he's made us proud. Such humble beginnings, and look at him now.
I've been crying happy tears all this tenday. What more could a mother want for her little boy?
You're not the only one he's hurt. Why would he do this?
What choice did we have?
Ah, saer, be very welcome to the family home of the soon-sworn Archduke, Enver Gortash!
There has to be another way. I deserve to live again - I deserve my own life!
*You focus on the source of the power, but it is quiet and still. It needs to rest.*
Welcome back!
Pardon us, saer. This house is in mourning.
You will keep your magic in hand, saer. In our Enver's own home! Disgusting.
He sauntered in. 'Lord Gortash'. What a name. Conjured up like a cheap trick. Said he was back - for good - and he wanted to repay us for his childhood.
Still bitter after all these years. But we did what was best for him - for all of us.
I feel bad for Gortash. That's a first.
*Your tadpole lashes and recoils. The connection is broken.*
He said he wanted to make us 'powerless'.
At least we all lived - Enver included. But he didn't see it that way. Stormed in here like we were murderers and he was the hand of justice itself.
He infected you with a mind flayer tadpole. I have one too - but for now, they can't be cured.
Why would Enver do this to you?
You may disagree. Enver did. But we don't deserve this - this torment. You're the first person who's heard the real me in months.
My son! You've seen what he's like. Same now as when he was a boy. Hateful little wretch.
There has to be. I can't live like this. I'm trapped - trapped!
Help me. Gods, help me! Enver's ruined my mind. He's taken my body!
You had every choice. You sold your son to a warlock - that's unforgivable.
Show me what you have in stock.
My goodness! What are you doing?!
If you were me, you'd've sent him away too. Believe you me.
Leave.
There's nothing I can do for you, at least for now - I'm sorry.
I should've killed him when he was babe in my lap. He was a nasty little freak, even then. The bastard. The bastard!
Ah, saer, you've chosen a special day to visit the family home of Archduke Enver Gortash.
Come again soon!
We love our son Enver. We love him so much.
I should've slammed the door in his face. But I let him in, and he rammed some kind of worm in our eyes.
Gods - Gortash has a mother?! I assumed he sprang fully-formed from a lich's arsecrack or something.

EditorData.NodeContext: Aside, to the player, not too loud.

Text.Value: That's generations of tradition for you!
What exactly happened?
May he rest in peace, our lad.

Synopsis: Default dialogue for Gortash's mother, Sally Flymm, at Flymm Cobblers in the Lower City. Gortash tadpoled his parents, who sold him into slavery in his youth. They are aware of their state but cannot resist the tadpole's compulsion - which makes them appear as huge fans of their son.
